BT 1 0 0 1 0 69.1055 Tm 7.875 TL /F1 5.25 Tf 0 0 0 rg (A namespace allows a process to have its own set of resources that other processes can't see. A namespace limits what resources a process can see and access Main Types: - Mount \(mnt\): each process) Tj T* (to have its own root filesystem that no other processes can see - UTS: each process to have its own unique hostname and domain name. - PID: Every running process can have its own set of PID number) Tj T* (\(childs cant see parents\). Node = Group of processes. - Network \(net\): virtual network for each process. Each virtual network can have its own subnets, virtual network interfaces, routing tables, and firewalls) Tj T* (- Interprocess Communication \(ipc\): This also prevents data leakage by preventing two processes from sharing the same memory space - control group \(cgroup\): This namespace hides the identity of the) Tj T* (cgroup that a process is a member of - User: The User namespace allows a user to have different levels of privilege on different processes. For example, a user could have root-level privileges on one) Tj T* (process, but only normal-user privileges on another process. - Examples - Docker uses namespaces to isolate containers from each other and from host os - PID: E.g. each container could have the same) Tj T* (PID \(or different\). Each Process only sees the other processes it launches. So container cannot see any other processes of the system. - NET: give different network access to different containers - mnt: Give) Tj T* (different file access to differetn containers - uts: each container has individual name & domai name system - ipc: define which container can talk to whom - user: isolate user & group id - Firejail uses) Tj T* (namespace per Tab) Tj T* ET
